
Sam Bayo's Asun Delicacies Marketplace
A Decoupled Full-Stack AWS Cloud Infrastructure Project

Project Overview
This project demonstrates the transition from a local development environment to a production-ready cloud infrastructure. It hosts a dynamic marketplace for Asun (peppered goat meat), utilizing a decoupled architecture to ensure high availability, data persistence, and security.

Live Demo: 
http://108.130.223.150:8080/products] (http://108.130.223.150:8080/products)

Architecture
The application is built using a "Security-First" approach on AWS:

Compute (EC2): A Linux-based Amazon EC2 instance hosting the Node.js/Express backend.
Database (RDS): A decoupled Amazon RDS (PostgreSQL) instance for persistent order and product management.
Storage (S3): Amazon S3 bucket used for high-speed delivery of static assets (menu images).
Security: Integrated SSL/TLS encryption for database communication using AWS global-bundle certificates.


Key Technical Implementations

 1. Production Resilience (DevOps)
To ensure the application remains live 24/7 without requiring an active SSH session, I implemented background process orchestration:
bash
 Ensuring the service survives terminal logout
node index.js & disown
2. Secure Data Persistence
Configured the PostgreSQL client to require SSL/TLS encryption, ensuring that customer data (like orders) is never transmitted in plain text across the network.
3. Cloud Asset Management
Implemented S3 Bucket Policies to manage public read access for assets while maintaining restricted permissions for the bucket itself, solving common "Access Denied" hurdles in cloud deployments.

